Source: CBC (Canadian Broadcasting Corporation) News [edited]
http://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/prince-edward-island/story/2013/06/13/pei-strawberry-virus-584.html


Farmers work to prevent strawberry virus spread
------------------------------------------------
Growers have begun work to prevent further spread of a virus [disease] that has infected the fields of 2 Prince Edward Island (PEI) strawberry farms. The disease is the same as the one threatening Nova Scotia's strawberry industry. 'I've never seen anything of this magnitude,' [said a PEI] strawberry grower.

The plant illness is spread by the strawberry aphid. It weakens plants to the point where the berries themselves are undesirably small, or the plant fails to produce berries altogether.

The Department of Agriculture will sample as many fields as they can to find out the extent of the virus. It's still not clear exactly how many fields are infected. The province hopes to have more answers later this month [June 2013]. "There is no cure, the only option is eradication of the plant and/or the stand it's in." That means plowing under crops or pulling out infected plants [which] could be an expensive solution.

"It's not only your immediate crop for this year, but how do you manage it down the road in the next 2 to 3 years?" said the strawberry farmer. [Another] farmer affected by the pest said he expects to begin spraying his fields soon to kill the aphids and prevent the spread of the virus.

